1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
A Dumb Dragon's Special Presentation.

2
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Hello, everybody. It's me, Leosin, just warming everybody up before the show tonight just to let you know what's going on here.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Some of our adventurers have decided to put on a play.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:31,000
And that play is A Christmas Carol, and we're calling it A Dumb John's Christmas Carol.

5
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:37,000
It's based on the stage adaptation of Charles Dickens' original work, The Christmas Carol, obviously.

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
This one originally by Frederick Gaines.

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,000
There's so many recognizable voices that you're going to see on stage here, and we can't wait to share it with you.

8
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
So please grab your snacks, sit down in the front row here.

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Yes, I see you, Arvid. You just have a seat there and we'll get the show going.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Alright, stage is set. I'm getting word that everybody's ready.

11
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
And we hope you enjoy this presentation of A Dumb John's Christmas Carol.

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
The play begins amid a swirl of street life in Victorian London.

13
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Happy groups pass, brightly costumed carolers and families call out to one another and sing.

14
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Joy to the world!

15
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Softly as the children talk.

16
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
I've got to get over and clean out the fireplace and Miss Brickenstone's.

17
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,000
I love being a child.

18
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,000
A child in Victorian England is fantastic. Look at that chimney. It's fun.

19
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Let's go! Play in the chimney!

20
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
My shift starts in three minutes.

21
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Bob Cratchit, a clerk who works in Scrooge's office, comes in.

22
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
He takes some coal from the mound and puts it into a small bucket.

23
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:02,000
Scrooge's nephew, Fred, enters, talks with the children, gives them coins and sends them away.

24
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:04,000
With a Merry Christmas.

25
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Here you go. One for you and one for you and three for you.

26
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Merry Christmas, Uncle! Bahamut save you!

27
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Bah, humbug.

28
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Christmas is a humbug, Uncle.

29
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
I hope that's meant as a joke.

30
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:19,000
Well, it's not.

31
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Come, what do you want? Don't waste my time. I don't have all day, nephew.

32
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
I only want to wish you a Merry Christmas, Uncle.

33
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Don't be a jerk about it.

34
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Well, what else can I be when I live in such a world of fools as this?

35
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Merry Christmas.

36
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Well, let's out with Merry Christmas.

37
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:40,000
What's Christmas to you but a time for paying all your bills with no money, by the way?

38
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,000
And a time for finding yourself a year older but no richer?

39
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Richer? If I could work my will, every idiot who would go about with Merry Christmas on his lips

40
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:55,000
would be boiled in their own pudding and buried with a stick of holly through his heart.

41
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Oh, that is a vivid picture, Uncle.

42
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:04,000
So nephew, keep Christmas in your own way and let me keep it in mine.

43
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:05,000
But you don't keep it.

44
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:07,000
That's right I don't, so you should leave it alone.

45
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
Because good may it do you. Much good has it ever done you.

46
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:15,000
There are a lot of things that I love that don't make me money.

47
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:18,000
Like, you know, when you get up super early and go on a really long run

48
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,000
and then you plank for like 40 minutes and like that doesn't put any money in my pocket.

49
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
But I love it so it's worth it.

50
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
And that's what Christmas is all about.

51
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
It's done a lot of good for me.

52
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And I say, bah hamet blesset.

53
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Bah.

54
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,000
Don't be angry, Uncle.

55
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Come, have dinner with us tomorrow.

56
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Zumba after dinner.

57
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Oh, yeah, no thanks. I'll dine alone.

58
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
But why?

59
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Why?

60
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Why did you get married?

61
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Well, because I fell in love with a wonderful girl.

62
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
And I fell in love with myself.

63
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Good afternoon.

64
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Oh, Uncle, you never came to see me before I was married.

65
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
So how can you now say, well, now you're married so I'm not going to come?

66
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
I said good afternoon.

67
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
I'm sorry with all my heart to find you so determined.

68
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:07,000
But I've made the attempt to honor Christmas and I'm going to keep that good spirit to the last.

69
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
So a Merry Christmas to you, Uncle.

70
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
A good afternoon.

71
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
And a Happy New Year. Bahamats blessings.

72
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
Oh, good afternoon.

73
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
Fred hesitates as if to say something more.

74
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
He sees that Scrooge has gone to get a book down from the shelf and he starts to leave.

75
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
As he leaves, the doorbell rings.

76
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Bells!

77
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Is it necessary to always have the fucking bells?

78
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000
The gentlemen visitors enter, causing the doorbell to ring again.

79
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,000
Cratchit!

80
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,000
Yes, sir?

81
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
The bell, fool. See to it. Stop making the noise.

82
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:42,000
Yes, sir.

83
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
He goes to the entrance.

84
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Merry Christmas.

85
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
Wolves howling and a Merry Christmas.

86
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
It's for you, sir.

87
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:50,000
No, duh.

88
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
You're not receiving anybody here, are you?

89
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Show them in.

90
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Right this way.

91
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,000
The gentlemen visitors approach Scrooge.

92
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Yes? What?

93
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Scrooge and Marley's, I believe.

94
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:09,000
Have I the pleasure of addressing Mr. Scrooge or Mr. Marley?

95
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Well, let me see.

96
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Molly's dead.

97
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
Seven years tonight, so what do you think?

98
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Well, I...

99
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,000
What do you want?

100
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
I have no doubt that his kindness is well represented by you, his surviving partner.

101
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
Here, sir, our card.

102
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
He hands Scrooge his business card.

103
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Kindness? No doubt of it.

104
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,000
All right, all right. I can read. What do you want?

105
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,000
He returns to his work.

106
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,000
At this, the festive season of the year...

107
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,000
Yeah, festive my ass. It's winter and it's cold.

108
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Well, and you make a great point, and that's actually why we're here.

109
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:45,000
At this time of year, people might like to set aside just a little something for the poor and the penniless

110
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,000
and their suffering because they're outside and it's cold

111
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:52,000
and they don't even really have like shoes or socks or coats or roofs or food

112
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,000
and, you know, just sort of the common comforts.

113
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
People don't have those hundreds of thousands of them.

114
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Oh, are there no debtors' prisons?

115
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
Many, sir.

116
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:07,000
And the workhouse, is it still working?

117
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Yeah, it is still, although I do wish I could say it was not.

118
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And the poor law, is that still like in full strength then?

119
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Yes, sir.

120
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Well, I'm glad to hear it.

121
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:24,000
From what you said, I was afraid someone had stopped its operation altogether.

122
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Well, because it's such a terrible place and so many people are in need,

123
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:34,000
a few of us were hoping to raise some money to buy the poor some meat and drink and means of warmth

124
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
and, of course, we chose this time of year out of all of the times of year

125
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:43,000
because everybody feels their want so strongly and everybody's rejoicing in abundance

126
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,000
and what can I put down for you, sir?

127
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Nothing.

128
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Ah, you wish to be anonymous. Very generous.

129
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
I wish to be left alone.

130
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:58,000
And since you asked me what I wish, sir, that's my answer.

131
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:04,000
I don't make merry myself at Christmas and I can't afford to make lazy people merry either.

132
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:09,000
I help support the establishments that I have mentioned

133
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
and they cost enough money so those who are poorly must go there.

134
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Well, many can't go there and honestly many would rather die than go there.

135
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Okay, well, if they'd rather die they'd better do it and decrease the surplus population.

136
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:26,000
That's not my business. My business is my business.

137
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
It occupies me constantly.

138
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:34,000
He talks both to the gentleman visitors and himself while he thumbs through his books.

139
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:37,000
Ask a man to give up life and means. Fine thing.

140
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
What is it I want to know? Charity?

141
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,000
Damn charity.

142
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:45,000
His nose deep in his books, he vaguely hears the dinner bell being rung in the workhouse.

143
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:49,000
He looks up as if he has heard it but never focuses on the actual scene.

144
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:54,000
The warder of the poorhouse stands in a pool of light at the far left, slowly ringing a bell.

145
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:58,000
Dinner! Alright. Come and get it, yo.

146
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:03,000
The poorly clad, dirty residents of the poorhouse line up and file by to get their evening dish of gruel,

147
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:07,000
wordlessly accepting it and going back to eat listlessly in the gloom.

148
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:10,000
Scrooge returns to the business of his office.

149
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:15,000
The procession continues for a moment, then the image of the poorhouse is hidden by darkness.

150
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,000
The dejected gentleman visitors exit.

151
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Fucking lock the door, Cratchit!

152
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,000
Like, both of them, firmly.

153
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
God, draft is cold as Christmas blowing in here. Charity.

154
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Suddenly, carolers appear on the platform and a few phrases of their carol,

155
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:38,000
Angels we have heard high, are heard.

156
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Scrooge looks up.

157
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Cratchit!

158
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:44,000
As soon as Scrooge shouts, the carolers vanish and Cratchit begins to close up the shop.

159
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
Cratchit!

160
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:46,000
Yes, sir?

161
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
Well, to work, then?

162
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,000
It's evening, sir.

163
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,000
No duh.

164
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,000
It's Christmas evening, sir.

165
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
Oh. You want all day off tomorrow, I suppose.

166
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:04,000
I mean, yeah. Well, if it's convenient, sir.

167
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,000
Yeah, it's not convenient. It's not fair.

168
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:11,000
If I was to deduct half a crown from your salary for it.

169
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:12,000
You wouldn't.

170
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,000
You'd think yourself ill-used, wouldn't you?

171
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:19,000
And you still expect me to pay a day's wage for a day and no work?

172
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:21,000
It's only once a year, sir.

173
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
Be here all the earlier next morning.

174
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
I will, sir.

175
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,000
Get out of here.

176
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Yes, sir.

177
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:31,000
Merry Christmas, sir.

178
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Bah!

179
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:36,000
As soon as Cratchit opens the door, the sounds of the street begin, very bright and loud.

180
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Cratchit is caught up in a swell of people hurrying down the street.

181
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Children pull him along the top of an ice slide, and he runs and slides down it, disappearing in darkness as the stage suddenly is left almost empty.

182
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:52,000
Scrooge goes around the room, blowing out candles, talking to himself.

183
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,000
Christmas Eve.

184
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
Carolers. Bah!

185
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
There. Another day.

186
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:01,000
He opens his door and peers out.

187
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:07,000
Dark. Very dark. Now where are they?

188
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
The children are heard singing carols for a moment.

189
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,000
Oh, begging pennies for the songs, are they?

190
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:15,000
Oh, boy.

191
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:29,000
Grandma's not gonna run by while you're in here!

192
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
Hey! Quiet! Quiet! Shut the fuck up down there!

193
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:33,000
Get off now!

194
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:35,000
There, that's it.

195
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
It's black as pitch out there.

196
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:41,000
The house of Ebenezer Scrooge.

197
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,000
Yeah. Here's the key.

198
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:52,000
He turns the key towards the door, and the face of Jacob Marley, Scrooge's deceased business partner, swims out of the darkness.

199
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Scrooge watches, unable to speak.

200
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:00,000
He fumbles for a match, lights the lantern, and swings it towards the figure, which melts away.

201
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Scrooge fits the key in the lock and turns it as the door suddenly is opened from the inside by the porter, Sparset.

202
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
Scrooge is startled, then recovers.

203
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Sparset?

204
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:16,000
Yes, sir. It is I, Sparset.

205
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
Emerging from the shadows, where I live.

206
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:23,000
Okay, so hurry up. The door. Close it.

207
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Did you knock, sir?

208
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Knock? What the fuck? It's my house. What's the matter?

209
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Never mind. Just give me some light up the stairs.

210
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:34,000
Yes, sir. I will push back the darkness for you.

211
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,000
He leads Scrooge up the stairs. They pass the cook on the way.

212
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:44,000
Scrooge brushes by here, stops, looks back, and leans towards him.

213
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:48,000
Uh, something to warm you, sir.

214
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:50,000
Porch? It's your favorite.

215
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:51,000
What?

216
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,000
It's bland. Flavorless.

217
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,000
No. No, nothing.

218
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:58,000
Waiting for her Christmas coin.

219
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:03,000
Merry Christmas, sir.

220
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
Scrooge ignores the request, and the cook disappears.

221
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Mumbling, Scrooge follows Sparset.

222
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Fucking good.

223
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,000
Looking back after the cook has gone.

224
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:19,000
Right at the end of his life. Merry Christmas.

225
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,000
Bah!

226
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,000
Your room, sir!

227
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
Okay, yeah, it's my... You don't have to... Listen, okay.

228
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:28,000
You don't have to announce every single fucking room we go into, okay?

229
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:31,000
It's my house. I know it's my room. Good night.

230
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:33,000
Understood.

231
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
Extending his hand for his coin.

232
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,000
Merry Christmas, sir.

233
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:39,000
Yes, yes.

234
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
He sees the outstretched hand.

235
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,000
He knows what Sparset wants, and is infuriated.

236
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:48,000
No! Out! Get out!

237
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:53,000
He closes the door after Sparset, turns towards his chamber,

238
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:58,000
and discovers the Char Woman, a woman hired to do the cleaning, directly behind him.

239
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,000
I'll warm your bed for you, sir!

240
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:04,000
What, like, you get in and roll around in it before I get in?

241
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:09,000
That's weird and unnecessary. No! Out! Get out!

242
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,000
Aye, sir.

243
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
She starts for the door. Marley's voice is heard mumbling something unintelligible.

244
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Why you gotta be so rude?

245
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:23,000
What's that? Is it magic?

246
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:26,000
Me, sir? Not a thing, sir.

247
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:29,000
Yeah, okay. Good night, then. Go.

248
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,000
Good night.

249
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:35,000
She exits, and Scrooge pantomimes, shutting the door behind her.

250
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:40,000
The voice of Marley over an offstage microphone whispers and reverberates.

251
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Merry Christmas, Scrooge!

252
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:48,000
Silence.

253
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:51,000
Scrooge hears the voice, but cannot account for it.

254
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:54,000
He climbs up to an open window, and looks down.

255
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:56,000
A cathedral choir singing,

256
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:01,000
O come all ye table,

257
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,000
is heard in the distance.

258
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:07,000
Scrooge listens a moment, shuts the window, and prepares for bed.

259
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:11,000
As soon as he has shut the sound out of his room, figures appear.

260
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:15,000
They seem to be coming down the main aisle of a church, bearing gifts to the living nursery.

261
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
The orchestra plays as the procession files out.

262
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Scrooge, ready for bed, warms himself before the heap of coals.

263
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:35,000
As he pulls his nightcap from a chair, a small handbell tumbles off onto the floor.

264
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:39,000
Startled, he picks it up and rings it for reassurance.

265
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
An echo answers it.

266
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
Scrooge escapes to his bed.

267
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:51,000
The bell sounds grow to a din, incoherent as in a dream, then suddenly fall silent.

268
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,000
Scrooge sits up in bed, listens, hears the chains of Marley coming up the stairs.

269
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Scrooge reaches for the bell pole to summon Sparset.

270
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:02,000
The bell responds with a gong, and Marley appears.

271
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
He and Scrooge face one another.

272
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:06,000
Oh, hi, Scrooge!

273
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Hey, it's me!

274
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:10,000
